{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"5f8c34fb-af8e-4508-9fbc-4ae219e806d6","content":"Use `Assert.ThrowsException<T>` (MSTest) or `Assert.Throws<T>` (xUnit/NUnit) instead:\n\n```csharp\n[TestMethod]\npublic void CreateUser_NullEmail_ThrowsException()\n{\n    var service = new UserService();\n\n    var ex = Assert.ThrowsException<ArgumentNullException>(\n        () => service.CreateUser(null, \"John\"));\n\n    Assert.AreEqual(\"email\", ex.ParamName); // optional: verify details\n}\n```\n\n**Why switch:**\n- `[ExpectedException]` passes if *any* line throws, masking bugs (e.g., the constructor throwing instead of `CreateUser`)\n- `Assert.ThrowsException` pins the exception to the exact call\n- You can inspect the exception object (message, inner exception, etc.)","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"a6b2b3b9-ae03-48b3-90a6-352ced0cdb59","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about modernizing a C# test that uses the `[ExpectedException]` attribute. This is a general knowledge question — no need to explore any codebase.","outputTokens":257,"requestId":"480E:4804C:8116F6:94E901:69FBEA05"},"id":"41d66e67-590f-4d00-922e-1ef93f3f3c39","timestamp":"2026-05-07T01:25:31.100Z","parentId":"6cdae52d-43bc-4898-8ea7-801c2a5d0da5"}
